Identified Weakness:
The rule relies solely on high-volume thresholds, causing delayed detection and missing early-stage suspicious behavior (especially during off-hours).

Before (Existing Rule):

OfficeActivity
| where TimeGenerated > ago(30m)
| where Workload == "SharePoint"
| where Operation == "FileDownloaded"
| summarize DownloadCount = count(), TotalBytes = sum(FileSize) by UserId, bin(TimeGenerated, 5m)
| where DownloadCount > 200 or TotalBytes > 2000000000
| project TimeGenerated, UserId, DownloadCount, TotalBytes

After (Improved Rule):
// Detect abnormal SharePoint downloads with basic behavioral context (time-of-day)

OfficeActivity
| where TimeGenerated > ago(30m)
| where Workload == "SharePoint"
| where Operation == "FileDownloaded"

// Aggregate user download behavior in short intervals
| summarize DownloadCount = count(), TotalBytes = sum(FileSize) 
    by UserId, bin(TimeGenerated, 5m)

// Add time-of-day context (business hours vs after-hours)
| extend Hour = datetime_part("hour", TimeGenerated)
| extend AfterHours = iff(Hour < 8 or Hour > 21, 1, 0)

// Trigger conditions:
// 1. Original high-volume threshold (kept for strong signals)
// 2. Lower threshold if activity occurs after-hours
| where 
    (DownloadCount > 200 or TotalBytes > 2000000000)  // existing baseline
    or (AfterHours == 1 and DownloadCount > 50)       // earlier detection for unusual timing

| project TimeGenerated, UserId, DownloadCount, TotalBytes, AfterHours

Explanation:

Detection Accuracy:
By adding time-of-day context, the rule now distinguishes between expected business activity and suspicious behavior, improving relevance without needing external data sources.

Noise Reduction:
Instead of lowering thresholds globally (which would create noise), thresholds are reduced only for after-hours activity — a strong behavioral anomaly in this case.

Earlier Detection:
The improved rule would have triggered much earlier (around the initial spike), rather than waiting until 2GB+ was already downloaded. This enables faster response during the early stages of data staging.